### Split Priority

> Tries paragraph breaks first, then lines, then spaces, then characters.

| Priority | Separator | Represents        |
|----------|-----------|-------------------|
| 1st      | `\n\n`    | Paragraph breaks  |
| 2nd      | `\n`      | Line breaks       |
| 3rd      | `" "`     | Spaces            |
| 4th      | `""`      | Characters        |

---

### Chunk Size Guidelines

| Use Case          | Chunk Size    | Overlap   | Why       |
|-------------------|---------------|-----------|-----------|
| Q&A / FAQ         | 500 - 800     | 50 - 100  | Precision |
| Documentation     | 1000 - 1500   | 200       | Context   |
| Code              | 1500 - 2000   | 200       | Functions |
| Books / Articles  | 800 - 1200    | 150       | Balance   |


#### Chunk Size Scale

| Too Small | Optimal | Too Large |
|-----------|---------|-----------|
| в—„в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ|в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җ|в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв–ә |

---

RFI (Request for Information) and RFP (Request for Proposal) documents often have a **Q&A** or **requirements-list** structure, so the FAQ chunking strategy (500вҖ“800 tokens, 50вҖ“100 overlap) is generally the right starting point. Each question/requirement is discrete and self-contained, so smaller chunks help the retriever return the precise answer to a specific question.

However, RFPs in particular can blur the line depending on the section. For example:

- **Q&A / requirements sections** вҶ’ chunk as FAQ (500вҖ“800 tokens). Precise retrieval of specific answers.
- **Scope of work or technical approach sections** вҶ’ these are more narrative and interconnected, so bumping up closer to the Documentation range (1000вҖ“1500 tokens) may work better.
- **Compliance or legal sections** вҶ’ similar to documentation, context between clauses matters.

So the practical advice is: **don't treat the whole RFP as one type**. Split it by section type and apply different chunking strategies per section. This hybrid approach tends to outperform using a single chunk size across the entire document.

